Effective Formulas

Posted on July 31, 2012  by  drowland 


Vitamost® food-based medicines are so effective primarily because they are formulated for totality, by Prof. David W. Rowland.  Each formula is like a symphony orchestra, with certain instruments playing lead parts and others supporting roles.  And every instrument influences the result.
Nutrients work interactively with each other.  Every factor needed by the body (for a particular purpose) has to be present in optimal amounts and must also have its supporting co-partners present in optimal amounts.  If even one nutrient is lacking, the formula becomes like the proverbial chain that is only as strong as its weakest link.
The body has its own wisdom.  It heals itself, if given the raw materials it needs.  Each   formulas provides a buffet of all of the factors the body needs to do a particular job.  And if everything it could possibly use is provided, the body selectively chooses what it needs and in proportion to its need.  Just as you eat more when you’re hungry and less when you’re not, the body consumes large portions of what it lacks and little or none of what it doesn’t need.
Each of is unique biochemically.  We are as different on the inside as we are on the outside.  Our bodies require the same nutrients, but in different proportions.  Every VItamost®  formula is so complete (for its purpose) that people with widely differing needs benefit from it.  Someone may have deficiencies in, say, four nutrients and also require another seven to assist in utilizing those four.  Others will need a quite different combination of nutrients and co-partners.  If all are present in optimal amounts, each person will get what their unique body requires.
David’s formulas also emphasize essential or primary nutrients – the ones that we have to get from our food supply because the body cannot produce them internally.  If the body gets enough of these basics, then it can produce all of the secondary or intermediate factors it needs – according to its own wisdom and priorities.  For example, if the body gets enough vitamin C, it can make all of the coenzyme Q-10 it needs.  Or if the body gets enough linoleic acid (e.g., from flaxseed oil) and enough vitamins and minerals, it can make all the gamma-linolenic acid it needs without having to take supplements of evening primrose oil.
Form of delivery also makes a difference to effectiveness.  Tablets are used for complex formulations, in order to prevent interaction of ingredients (e.g., choline reacting with vitamin C to produce choline ascorbate).  Capsules are used for ingredients that don’t interact.  Liquids are used for sublingual absorption of homeopathics.  Timed-release forms are never used because of their inefficiency; many people’s digestion isn’t strong enough to break down the multiple layers of wax on the ingredients, and many timed-release products end up in the toilet.
To view or buy Vitamost® supplements:  www.vitamost.com
 
 





